comment: I am processing a lot of emotions today, especially sadness and fear. I am impressed how this practice has shown me how important the focus on the present moment is. I NEVER have been so good in the balancing postures, because I found so much comfort in breathing and focusing on the balance. It was so comforting, I can‚Äôt explain it. like a silent way of ‚ÄúI am here fir you‚Äù, which my body, breath and mind told me. This sounds very spiritual but being able to stand in such a challenging posture so calmly and comfortable, it made me realize that I will go through everything. It‚Äôs going to be okay. Processing it, one emotion, one thought, one action, one word at the time. Slow healing.
Thank you for helping me processing

Have you ever cried about something that you did no even know you were sad about...? After practice, in shavasana I started thinking about how we, us humans, have to process loneliness, and how it manifests in so many various ways. I gradually calmed down and remembered that I do have a relationship with God, but there is a PROCESS of growth and inner healing that comes from interpersonal relationships with others that will allow me to experience more of God, in a deeper way. Yes, our shared journey is a beautiful gift to allow us, globally, to process, and be present with each other, in a higher place. You have prepared the space for us Adriene, as the gracious host you are. Time and Space, until we are ready to be our best and brightest for each other, and for the world.

last year was my first year doing the 30 days and it helped me find the courage to seek a diagnosis for a mental health disorder. having that diagnosis has helped me immensely but it's made me even more keenly aware of the tightrope i walk: on the one hand, i need a strict routine, checklists, workouts, sleeping schedule, etc in order to function - and yet i am much more susceptible to becoming overtired and burning out and so i also need to give myself lots of time to rest and recuperate. this last week i've started to notice myself teetering on the brink of burnout, starting to get lazy about good habits and slip back into bad ones, a pattern that has previously signaled the start of a depressive episode. this "process" practice gave me the space to, well, process that, to sift through how i've been feeling, to think about what serves me and what just tires me out. i didn't come to any answers but the balance flow offered such a beautiful model of what i'm trying to achieve and allowed me to be kind to myself and have some perspective on where i'm at in my ... yeah ... process.
